window.SEARCH_INDEX = [{"t": "The Pour Over Coffee Knowledge Base", "u": "index.html", "d": "Introduction", "i": "☕", "c": "#B07B4F", "s": "A comprehensive, interlinked knowledge base on pour over coffee — the craft of brewing by pouring hot water through ground coffee in a filter. Written for the intellectually curious: equally useful to someone brewing their first Hario V60 a", "k": "moc introduction home Home Index Start Here Pour Over Coffee Knowledge Base"}, {"t": "What Is Pour Over Coffee?", "u": "what-is-pour-over-coffee.html", "d": "Introduction", "i": "☕", "c": "#B07B4F", "s": "Pour over is a method of brewing coffee in which hot water is poured, by hand, over a bed of ground coffee held in a filter lined The Dripper Explained. Gravity pulls the water down through the coffee and the Coffee Filters — Paper, Metal, ", "k": "introduction fundamentals What Is Pour Over Coffee Pour over definition Pour over coffee"}, {"t": "Brew Method Family Tree", "u": "brew-method-family-tree.html", "d": "Introduction", "i": "☕", "c": "#B07B4F", "s": "Pour over is one branch of a much larger family of coffee brewing methods. This note maps how the methods relate so you can see where pour over sits; the Brew Method Comparison Table compares them by numbers, and Equipment and Drippers cove", "k": "introduction methods overview Brew Method Family Tree Brewing methods map Coffee method lineage"}, {"t": "How to Use This Knowledge Base", "u": "how-to-use-this-knowledge-base.html", "d": "Introduction", "i": "☕", "c": "#B07B4F", "s": "This vault is built for [Obsidian](https://obsidian.md) and is best explored as a web of linked notes rather than read front to back. It also publishes to a searchable website. The Structure Notes are grouped into twelve numbered folders, e", "k": "introduction meta guide How to Use This Knowledge Base Navigation guide Reading guide"}, {"t": "History of Pour Over Coffee", "u": "history-of-pour-over-coffee.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "The story of pour over is the story of people trying to get grit out of the cup without losing the flavor in it. For most of coffee's history, brewing meant boiling grounds in water and drinking around the sediment. The pour over we know to", "k": "history origins overview moc History of Pour Over Coffee Pour over history History of filter coffee"}, {"t": "Origins of Filter Coffee", "u": "origins-of-filter-coffee.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "Before there was a filter, there was mud . The earliest coffee — brewed in the Arabian Peninsula and across the Ottoman world — was made by boiling finely ground beans directly in water, a tradition that survives today as Turkish and simila", "k": "history origins filter drip Origins of Filter Coffee Early filter coffee Pre-paper brewing"}, {"t": "Melitta Bentz and the Paper Filter", "u": "melitta-bentz-and-the-paper-filter.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "In 1908, a Dresden housewife named Melitta Bentz did something every coffee drinker of her era had wished for: she got the grounds out of the cup for good. Frustrated by the bitter, gritty coffee that cloth filters and percolators produced,", "k": "history melitta paper-filter invention Melitta Bentz and the Paper Filter Melitta Bentz The paper filter"}, {"t": "The Rise of Drip Coffee", "u": "the-rise-of-drip-coffee.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "Melitta Bentz and the Paper Filter solved the grit problem, but it took the better part of the 20th century for drip coffee to become the default way the Western world made its morning cup. The arc runs from manual pour over cones, through ", "k": "history drip automatic twentieth-century The Rise of Drip Coffee Rise of drip coffee Drip coffee history"}, {"t": "⏳ Chemex and Peter Schlumbohm", "u": "chemex-and-peter-schlumbohm.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "In 1941, a German born chemist named Peter Schlumbohm patented a coffee brewer that looked less like kitchenware and more like laboratory glass — because that is exactly what inspired it. The Chemex is a single piece of borosilectate glass ", "k": "history chemex design invention Chemex and Peter Schlumbohm Peter Schlumbohm Chemex history"}, {"t": "Japanese Coffee Culture and the Kissaten", "u": "japanese-coffee-culture-and-the-kissaten.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "If the paper filter was born in Germany, the art of pour over was perfected in Japan. From the early 20th century, Japan developed a deep, idiosyncratic coffee culture centered on the kissaten (喫茶店) — traditional cafés where coffee was trea", "k": "history japan kissaten culture craft Japanese Coffee Culture and the Kissaten Kissaten Japanese coffee culture"}, {"t": "The Siphon and Nel Drip Tradition", "u": "the-siphon-and-nel-drip-tradition.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "Pour over did not evolve in isolation. Alongside it, especially in the Japanese Japanese Coffee Culture and the Kissaten, two other hand brewing arts were refined to an extraordinary degree: siphon (vacuum) brewing and nel drip (cloth filte", "k": "history japan siphon nel-drip craft The Siphon and Nel Drip Tradition Siphon coffee Nel drip"}, {"t": "Hario and the V60", "u": "hario-and-the-v60.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "No single object says \"pour over\" like the Hario V60 . A simple cone of ribbed plastic, glass, ceramic, or metal, it became — within a decade of its 2004 launch — the global symbol of manual coffee. The company behind it, Hario , was founde", "k": "history hario v60 dripper icon Hario and the V60 Hario history The V60 story"}, {"t": "The Specialty Coffee Movement", "u": "the-specialty-coffee-movement.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "Pour over's modern revival was not really about gear — it was about a new way of thinking about coffee as an agricultural product with origin character , the way wine drinkers think about a vineyard. That shift is the specialty coffee movem", "k": "history specialty scaa movement quality The Specialty Coffee Movement Specialty coffee movement Specialty coffee history"}, {"t": "First, Second, and Third Wave Coffee", "u": "first-second-and-third-wave-coffee.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "The most common way people narrate modern coffee history is the \"wave\" framework — three (and now four) successive eras, each redefining what coffee meant. It is a genuinely useful shorthand for understanding how we got from canned supermar", "k": "history waves framework culture \"First Second and Third Wave Coffee\" Coffee waves Third wave coffee"}, {"t": "The Modern Pour Over Renaissance", "u": "the-modern-pour-over-renaissance.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "Something remarkable happened in the 2010s: brewing coffee by hand at home went from a niche hobby to a global movement with its own celebrities, gear culture, and shared vocabulary. The Hario and the V60 was a few dollars, The Specialty Co", "k": "history renaissance home-brewing content recipes The Modern Pour Over Renaissance Pour over renaissance Modern pour over revival"}, {"t": "The Future of Pour Over", "u": "the-future-of-pour-over.html", "d": "History & Origins", "i": "📜", "c": "#9B6A43", "s": "Where does a craft go once it has been perfected by hand and documented to the gram? The final chapter of this History of Pour Over Coffee looks forward — to automation, smarter brewers, sustainability pressures, and an open question about ", "k": "history future automation sustainability technology The Future of Pour Over Future of pour over Pour over future"}, {"t": "Equipment and Drippers", "u": "equipment-and-drippers.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "This is the map of the gear that turns ground coffee and hot water into a finished cup. Pour over is famously low barrier — a single The Dripper Explained, a Coffee Filters — Paper, Metal, and Cloth, and any source of hot water will brew a ", "k": "equipment drippers gear hub moc Equipment and Drippers Pour over gear Brewing equipment"}, {"t": "The Dripper Explained", "u": "the-dripper-explained.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "A dripper is the cone or basket shaped vessel that holds the filter and coffee bed while water passes through it. It looks simple, but its geometry is the single biggest piece of hardware deciding how your coffee tastes. Every design choice", "k": "equipment drippers anatomy fundamentals The Dripper Explained Dripper anatomy Coffee dripper"}, {"t": "Conical vs Flat Bottom Drippers", "u": "conical-vs-flat-bottom-drippers.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The most consequential choice in pour over hardware is geometry : does the coffee bed taper to a point, or sit flat across the bottom? This single fork explains most of the personality difference between a Hario V60 and a Kalita Wave, and i", "k": "equipment drippers geometry extraction Conical vs Flat Bottom Drippers Cone vs flat Dripper geometry"}, {"t": "Dripper Materials and Heat Retention", "u": "dripper-materials-and-heat-retention.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "A dripper of identical shape can be made from ceramic, plastic, glass, or metal — and the choice is not just cosmetic. Material governs thermal mass : how much heat the dripper absorbs from your water and how steady the brew temperature sta", "k": "equipment drippers materials temperature Dripper Materials and Heat Retention Dripper material Thermal mass"}, {"t": "Hario V60", "u": "hario-v60.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The Hario V60 is the most iconic pour over dripper in the world — the brewer that, more than any other, defines the modern image of manual coffee. Launched by Japanese glassware maker Hario in 2004, its name comes from its shape: a V shaped", "k": "equipment drippers v60 conical Hario V60 V60 Hario"}, {"t": "Kalita Wave", "u": "kalita-wave.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The Kalita Wave is the most beloved flat bottom dripper and the V60's natural counterpoint. Made by the Japanese brand Kalita, it trades the cone's demanding precision for evenness and forgiveness , producing a sweet, balanced, well rounded", "k": "equipment drippers kalita flat-bottom Kalita Wave Kalita Wave dripper"}, {"t": "⏳ Chemex", "u": "chemex.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The Chemex is the most elegant object in coffee — an hourglass shaped, all in one glass decanter that is simultaneously the dripper and the server. Designed in 1941 by chemist Peter Schlumbohm (see Chemex and Peter Schlumbohm), it is a perm", "k": "equipment drippers chemex conical Chemex Chemex brewer"}, {"t": "Origami Dripper", "u": "origami-dripper.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The Origami Dripper is the great shape shifter of pour over. Made in Japan's ceramic town of Mino, its faceted, pleated walls — the source of its name — make it a darling of cafés and a competition favorite. Its trick is versatility : depen", "k": "equipment drippers origami versatile Origami Dripper Origami"}, {"t": "Flat Bottom Drippers — April and Orea", "u": "flat-bottom-drippers-april-and-orea.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "While the Kalita Wave defined the classic flat bottom, a new generation of fast flowing flat brewers has emerged from the specialty scene — led by the Danish roaster April and the British designed Orea. These drippers keep the flat bed's ev", "k": "equipment drippers flat-bottom modern \"Flat Bottom Drippers — April and Orea\" April Brewer Orea Brewer"}, {"t": "Melitta and Wedge Drippers", "u": "melitta-and-wedge-drippers.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "Before the V60 or the Kalita, there was the Melitta — the dripper that invented the category. In 1908 the German housewife Melitta Bentz punched holes in a brass pot and lined it with blotting paper, creating the first paper filter pour ove", "k": "equipment drippers melitta history Melitta and Wedge Drippers Melitta dripper Wedge dripper"}, {"t": "The Clever Dripper", "u": "the-clever-dripper.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The Clever Dripper is the brilliant compromise between pour over and immersion. It looks like a chunky cone, but a shut off valve in the base changes everything: set it on the counter and it holds water like a steeping pot; set it on your m", "k": "equipment drippers immersion clever The Clever Dripper Clever Dripper Clever"}, {"t": "AeroPress", "u": "aeropress.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The AeroPress is the most versatile brewer in coffee — a plastic cylinder and plunger that combines immersion steeping with gentle pressure to push the brew through a paper filter. Invented in 2005 by Alan Adler (the engineer behind the Aer", "k": "equipment drippers aeropress immersion hybrid AeroPress Aeropress"}, {"t": "OXO Rapid Brewer", "u": "oxo-rapid-brewer.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The OXO Rapid Brewer (also called the OXO Brew Rapid Brewer) is a recent immersion and drain hybrid that aims to make a flat bottom, paper clean cup almost foolproof. Like the The Clever Dripper, it steeps the coffee bed and then releases t", "k": "equipment drippers oxo immersion hybrid OXO Rapid Brewer Oxo Rapid Brewer Rapid Brewer"}, {"t": "French Press", "u": "french-press.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The French Press is the benchmark of full immersion brewing — and the contrasting pole to every paper pour over in this vault. Coffee steeps fully submerged in hot water, then a metal mesh plunger presses the grounds to the bottom, separati", "k": "equipment drippers french-press immersion French Press Cafetiere Press pot"}, {"t": "Coffee Filters — Paper, Metal, and Cloth", "u": "coffee-filters-paper-metal-and-cloth.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The filter is the unsung hero of pour over. It holds the grounds back and quietly decides how much of the coffee's oils and fine particles reach your cup — which is to say, it decides much of the cup's clarity and body . The same coffee in ", "k": "equipment filters paper metal cloth \"Coffee Filters — Paper Metal and Cloth\" Coffee filters Filter types"}, {"t": "Gooseneck Kettles", "u": "gooseneck-kettles.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The gooseneck kettle is the second most iconic piece of pour over gear after the dripper itself — and arguably the one that most improves a beginner's coffee. Its long, curved, narrow spout gives you precise control over where, how fast, an", "k": "equipment kettle temperature pouring Gooseneck Kettles Gooseneck kettle Pour over kettle"}, {"t": "Scales, Timers, and Servers", "u": "scales-timers-and-servers.html", "d": "Equipment & Drippers", "i": "⚙️", "c": "#6E7E8A", "s": "The dripper and kettle get the glory, but scales, timers, and servers are what turn a lucky cup into a repeatable one. They are cheap, unglamorous, and quietly transformative: weighing your dose and water, watching the clock, and catching t", "k": "equipment scale timer server accessories \"Scales Timers and Servers\" Coffee scale Brewing accessories"}, {"t": "Coffee Beans and Roast", "u": "coffee-beans-and-roast.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "No brewing technique can rescue a bad bean, and no bean reveals itself without thoughtful roasting and brewing. This domain follows the bean's journey — from a flowering tropical shrub to the fragrant grounds in your The Dripper Explained —", "k": "coffee-beans roast origin processing hub Coffee Beans and Roast Beans and roast The bean domain"}, {"t": "The Coffee Plant — Arabica and Robusta", "u": "the-coffee-plant-arabica-and-robusta.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Coffee comes from the seeds of Coffea , a genus of tropical evergreen shrubs that produce small fruits called cherries . Inside each cherry sit two green seeds — the beans we eventually roast. Of the 120 plus known Coffea species, only two ", "k": "coffee-beans botany arabica robusta species \"The Coffee Plant — Arabica and Robusta\" Arabica vs Robusta Coffee species"}, {"t": "Coffee Varietals", "u": "coffee-varietals.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "If The Coffee Plant — Arabica and Robusta is the broad category, a varietal (more precisely a cultivar ) is the specific genetic line within it — coffee's equivalent of a grape variety like Pinot Noir or Chardonnay. Variety helps determine ", "k": "coffee-beans varietals genetics geisha bourbon Coffee Varietals Coffee varieties Cultivars"}, {"t": "Coffee Growing Regions and Terroir", "u": "coffee-growing-regions-and-terroir.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Terroir — borrowed from wine — is the idea that place leaves a fingerprint on flavor. A coffee's origin, altitude, soil, rainfall, and climate all shape the chemistry of the bean before it is ever Coffee Processing Methods or Coffee Roastin", "k": "coffee-beans terroir origin regions altitude Coffee Growing Regions and Terroir Terroir Growing regions Coffee origins"}, {"t": "Coffee Processing Methods", "u": "coffee-processing-methods.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Between a ripe coffee cherry picked off a tree and a green bean ready to Coffee Roasting Explained lies processing — the post harvest work of removing the fruit and drying the seed. It sounds like mere logistics, but it is one of the most p", "k": "coffee-beans processing post-harvest green-coffee Coffee Processing Methods Processing Post-harvest processing Coffee processing"}, {"t": "Washed Process", "u": "washed-process.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "The washed (or wet ) process is the clarity benchmark of coffee. By removing all the fruit before the bean dries, it strips away the variables of Natural Process fruit drying and lets the underlying Coffee Growing Regions and Terroir and Co", "k": "coffee-beans processing washed wet-process Washed Process Wet process Washed coffee"}, {"t": "Natural Process", "u": "natural-process.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "The natural (or dry ) process is the oldest method of all — coffee was processed this way for centuries before water washing existed — and it produces the wildest, fruitiest cups in coffee. Instead of stripping the fruit away as in the Wash", "k": "coffee-beans processing natural dry-process Natural Process Dry process Natural coffee Dry-processed coffee"}, {"t": "Honey and Experimental Processing", "u": "honey-and-experimental-processing.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Between the clean Washed Process and the wild Natural Process sits a growing world of honey and experimental methods that deliberately tune fermentation and fruit contact to engineer specific flavors. This is the modern frontier of coffee —", "k": "coffee-beans processing honey anaerobic experimental \"Honey and Experimental Processing\" Honey process Anaerobic processing Carbonic maceration"}, {"t": "Coffee Roasting Explained", "u": "coffee-roasting-explained.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Green coffee is nearly flavorless — grassy, dense, and inert. Roasting is the application of heat that transforms it, through a cascade of chemical reactions, into the aromatic brown bean we grind and brew. It is the bridge between the Coff", "k": "coffee-beans roasting maillard first-crack chemistry Coffee Roasting Explained Roasting Coffee roasting Roast chemistry"}, {"t": "Roast Levels for Pour Over", "u": "roast-levels-for-pour-over.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Roast level is the bean variable that most directly changes how you brew . It runs along a continuous spectrum from light to dark, set by how far past Coffee Roasting Explained the roaster takes the bean. For pour over and filter brewing in", "k": "coffee-beans roast roast-levels extraction filter Roast Levels for Pour Over Roast levels Roast spectrum Filter roast"}, {"t": "Light Roast and Specialty Coffee", "u": "light-roast-and-specialty-coffee.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "Over the last two decades, light roasting went from a curiosity to the defining house style of The Specialty Coffee Industry. Championed by Scandinavian roasters and spread by the The Specialty Coffee Movement, the light roast philosophy tr", "k": "coffee-beans roast light-roast specialty extraction Light Roast and Specialty Coffee Light roast Nordic roast"}, {"t": "Coffee Freshness and Degassing", "u": "coffee-freshness-and-degassing.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "A perfectly grown, processed, and roasted coffee can still brew badly if it is too young, too old, or poorly stored. Freshness is a moving target: roasted coffee needs a few days to settle before it brews well, then a few weeks of peak, the", "k": "coffee-beans freshness degassing co2 storage Coffee Freshness and Degassing Degassing Coffee freshness Resting coffee"}, {"t": "Reading a Coffee Bag Label", "u": "reading-a-coffee-bag-label.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "A specialty coffee bag is a dense little dossier. Learning to read it lets you predict how a coffee will taste and how to brew it before you ever open the bag — and it teaches you to spot the roasters who value transparency over marketing. ", "k": "coffee-beans buying label transparency traceability Reading a Coffee Bag Label Decoding a coffee label Coffee bag label"}, {"t": "Single Origin vs Blends", "u": "single-origin-vs-blends.html", "d": "Coffee Beans & Roast", "i": "🌱", "c": "#7A9A3E", "s": "When you buy coffee, you face a basic fork: a single origin that showcases one place, or a blend that combines several for a designed effect. Pour over culture overwhelmingly favors single origin — but understanding both, and the marketing ", "k": "coffee-beans single-origin blends buying sourcing Single Origin vs Blends Single origin Coffee blends Single origin vs blend"}, {"t": "Grinding", "u": "grinding.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "Grinding is the act of reducing roasted whole beans to particles ready for brewing — and it is arguably the single most important variable a pour over brewer controls. Grinding determines the surface area the water meets, and surface area g", "k": "grinding fundamentals hub Grinding Grinding coffee The grind"}, {"t": "Why Grind Size Matters", "u": "why-grind-size-matters.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "Grind size is the master lever of pour over because it sets the pace of The Science of Extraction more directly than any other single variable. When you grind a bean, you do two things at once: you create vast new surface area , and you sho", "k": "grinding fundamentals extraction Why Grind Size Matters Grind size importance Why grind matters"}, {"t": "Burr Grinders vs Blade Grinders", "u": "burr-grinders-vs-blade-grinders.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "Not all grinders are created equal — and the gap between a burr grinder and a blade grinder is the largest single equipment upgrade most home brewers can make. The difference comes down to one word: uniformity . Burrs produce particles of a", "k": "grinding equipment fundamentals Burr Grinders vs Blade Grinders Burr vs blade Burr grinder"}, {"t": "Conical vs Flat Burrs", "u": "conical-vs-flat-burrs.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "Once you have committed to a Burr Grinders vs Blade Grinders, the next fork is geometry : conical or flat. Both crush beans between abrasive surfaces, but their shapes route coffee through the grinding zone differently, and that shapes the ", "k": "grinding equipment contested Conical vs Flat Burrs Conical burrs Flat burrs"}, {"t": "Grind Size for Pour Over", "u": "grind-size-for-pour-over.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "So where exactly should you set the grinder? Pour over lives in a medium grind window — coarser than espresso, finer than French Press — but the precise target shifts with your The Dripper Explained, your Roast Levels for Pour Over, and you", "k": "grinding fundamentals technique Grind Size for Pour Over Pour over grind size Pour over grind"}, {"t": "Particle Distribution and Uniformity", "u": "particle-distribution-and-uniformity.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "A grind is never a single size — it is a distribution of sizes around a target. Plot how many particles fall at each diameter and you get the grinder's signature curve. The shape of that curve, not just its center point, decides how evenly ", "k": "grinding science fundamentals Particle Distribution and Uniformity Grind distribution Grind uniformity"}, {"t": "Fines and Boulders", "u": "fines-and-boulders.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "At the two ends of every grind's Particle Distribution and Uniformity sit the troublemakers: fines and boulders . Fines are the smallest particles — near dust; boulders are the largest — oversized chunks. A little of each is inevitable, but", "k": "grinding science troubleshooting Fines and Boulders Fines Boulders"}, {"t": "Dialing In Grind Size", "u": "dialing-in-grind-size.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "Every coffee has a grind setting that makes it sing — and dialing in is the simple, disciplined loop you use to find it: brew, taste, adjust grind, re brew. Because grind is the Why Grind Size Matters of The Science of Extraction, it is als", "k": "grinding technique troubleshooting Dialing In Grind Size Dialing in grind Adjusting grind"}, {"t": "Hand Grinders vs Electric Grinders", "u": "hand-grinders-vs-electric-grinders.html", "d": "Grinding", "i": "🔩", "c": "#A8762F", "s": "Once you've chosen a Burr Grinders vs Blade Grinders and thought about Conical vs Flat Burrs, one practical question remains: do you turn it by hand or plug it in? Both hand (manual) and electric grinders can deliver excellent, uniform pour", "k": "grinding equipment Hand Grinders vs Electric Grinders Hand grinders Manual vs electric grinders"}, {"t": "Water for Coffee", "u": "water-for-coffee.html", "d": "Water", "i": "💧", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "A finished cup of pour over is roughly 98–99% water by mass — the coffee solubles you worked so hard to extract make up barely one or two percent of what reaches your lips. That arithmetic alone explains why water is the most underrated ing", "k": "water fundamentals hub Water for Coffee Brewing water Coffee water"}, {"t": "Why Water Matters", "u": "why-water-matters.html", "d": "Water", "i": "💧", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Because a brewed coffee is about 98% water , the water you start with is not a backdrop to flavor — it is most of the flavor's physical home. Two brewers can use identical beans, the same Grind Size for Pour Over, the same The Brew Ratio, a", "k": "water fundamentals extraction Why Water Matters Importance of brewing water Water and flavor"}, {"t": "Water Chemistry — Hardness and Alkalinity", "u": "water-chemistry-hardness-and-alkalinity.html", "d": "Water", "i": "💧", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "The single most useful idea in coffee water chemistry is that hardness and alkalinity are two different things , even though everyday language tangles them together. Hardness — measured as GH , general hardness — is the amount of calcium an", "k": "water chemistry extraction \"Water Chemistry — Hardness and Alkalinity\" GH and KH Hardness and alkalinity"}, {"t": "TDS and Mineral Content", "u": "tds-and-mineral-content.html", "d": "Water", "i": "💧", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Total Dissolved Solids (TDS) is the total mass of dissolved substances in water, usually expressed in parts per million (ppm) or milligrams per litre (mg/L — the same number). For brewing water, that means everything dissolved before the co", "k": "water chemistry measurement TDS and Mineral Content Water TDS Mineral content"}, {"t": "The SCA Water Standard", "u": "the-sca-water-standard.html", "d": "Water", "i": "💧", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "The Specialty Coffee Association (SCA) — and before it the SCAA — publishes a recommended water profile for brewing, the closest thing the industry has to an agreed definition of \"good water.\" It exists because water is the great hidden var", "k": "water standards reference The SCA Water Standard SCA water standard SCAA water standard"}, {"t": "Water Temperature for Brewing", "u": "water-temperature-for-brewing.html", "d": "Water", "i": "💧", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "After mineral content, temperature is the strongest dial water gives you over the cup, because heat governs how fast coffee solubles dissolve. The widely accepted pour over window is roughly 90–96°C (195–205°F) , with much of the specialty ", "k": "water temperature extraction Water Temperature for Brewing Brew temperature Water temperature"}, {"t": "Building Water — Recipes and Remineralization", "u": "building-water-recipes-and-remineralization.html", "d": "Water", "i": "💧", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Once you understand that water is most of the cup, the logical next step is to stop hoping your tap is good and build your own to a known target. The recipe is always the same shape: start from near zero water — distilled or reverse osmosis", "k": "water chemistry recipes \"Building Water — Recipes and Remineralization\" Remineralization Building brewing water"}, {"t": "Filtered, Bottled, and Tap Water", "u": "filtered-bottled-and-tap-water.html", "d": "Water", "i": "💧", "c": "#3D7E96", "s": "Building water from scratch is the precise route, but most people brew with whatever comes out of a tap, a filter jug, or a bottle. The good news is that sensible everyday water can brew excellent coffee — you just need to know which source", "k": "water practical sources \"Filtered Bottled and Tap Water\" Water sources Everyday brewing water"}, {"t": "Brewing Technique", "u": "brewing-technique.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Brewing technique is everything the brewer actually does at the dripper — the controllable levers of a manual brew. If Grinding, Water for Coffee, and Coffee Beans and Roast are the ingredients, technique is the cooking: how you wet the bed", "k": "brewing-technique fundamentals hub Brewing Technique Pour over technique Brewing fundamentals"}, {"t": "The Anatomy of a Pour Over", "u": "the-anatomy-of-a-pour-over.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Every manual brew, from a humble Hario V60 to a four cup Chemex, follows the same arc. Knowing the stages turns a recipe from a list of numbers into a story you can read and adjust. This note maps the brew start to finish; the deeper craft ", "k": "brewing-technique fundamentals workflow The Anatomy of a Pour Over Stages of a pour over Pour over steps"}, {"t": "The Brew Ratio", "u": "the-brew-ratio.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "The brew ratio is the proportion of coffee to water — the single number that most directly sets how strong your cup will be. Written as (e.g. ), it tells you how many grams of water you pour per gram of coffee. Get this right and everything", "k": "brewing-technique ratio strength The Brew Ratio Coffee to water ratio Golden ratio Brew ratio"}, {"t": "The Bloom", "u": "the-bloom.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "The bloom is the first small pour of a brew — a brief pre infusion that wets all the grounds and lets trapped gas escape before the main pours begin. Watch fresh coffee bloom and you will see the bed swell, dome, and bubble like rising doug", "k": "brewing-technique bloom pre-infusion The Bloom Bloom Pre-infusion Coffee bloom"}, {"t": "Pouring Technique", "u": "pouring-technique.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "How you pour water is the most hands on lever in the whole brew. The same coffee, grind, and ratio can yield a clean, sweet cup or a hollow, sour one depending purely on where you pour, how high from, how fast , and how steadily you control", "k": "brewing-technique pouring kettle-control Pouring Technique How to pour Pour patterns Kettle control"}, {"t": "Pulse vs Continuous Pouring", "u": "pulse-vs-continuous-pouring.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Once the The Bloom is done, you face a choice that defines the rest of the brew: do you add the remaining water in several discrete pulses , or in one steady continuous stream? These are the two great pouring philosophies, and each shapes t", "k": "brewing-technique pouring strategy Pulse vs Continuous Pouring Pulse pouring Continuous pouring"}, {"t": "Agitation and Turbulence", "u": "agitation-and-turbulence.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Agitation is the physical energy you add to the coffee bed — through pour force, stirring, or swirling. It is one of the most powerful and least understood levers in pour over. More agitation means more extraction ; too much means harshness", "k": "brewing-technique agitation extraction Agitation and Turbulence Agitation Turbulence Stirring and swirling"}, {"t": "⏬ The Drawdown", "u": "the-drawdown.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "The drawdown is the final phase of a brew: after your last pour, the remaining water drains down through the coffee bed and out of the The Dripper Explained. It is the most diagnostic moment in pour over — how the bed drains tells you almos", "k": "brewing-technique drawdown diagnostics The Drawdown Drawdown Drain phase Drawdown time"}, {"t": "Bypass and Channeling", "u": "bypass-and-channeling.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Two related faults explain most disappointing pour overs: bypass , where water flows around the coffee instead of through it, and channeling , where water carves a preferred path through the bed and floods down it. Both mean some water unde", "k": "brewing-technique channeling faults Bypass and Channeling Channeling Bypass Uneven extraction"}, {"t": "Pre-Wetting the Filter", "u": "pre-wetting-the-filter.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Pre wetting — or rinsing — the paper Coffee Filters — Paper, Metal, and Cloth is the very first step of most pour over recipes: you pour hot water through the empty filter and discard it before adding coffee. It is nearly universal practice", "k": "brewing-technique filter preparation Pre-Wetting the Filter Rinsing the filter Filter rinse"}, {"t": "⏱️ Brew Time and Total Contact Time", "u": "brew-time-and-total-contact-time.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Total contact time is the span from your first drop of water to the last drip out of the The Dripper Explained — how long water and coffee are in contact. It is one of three big extraction levers alongside Grind Size for Pour Over and Water", "k": "brewing-technique timing diagnostics Brew Time and Total Contact Time Brew time Total contact time Contact time"}, {"t": "Single Cup vs Batch Pour Over", "u": "single-cup-vs-batch-pour-over.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Brewing one cup and brewing for a table are not the same act scaled up — they are different problems. As you increase the dose and water, the bed gets deeper , the water column gets taller , and the physics of The Drawdown and Extraction Yi", "k": "brewing-technique scaling batch Single Cup vs Batch Pour Over Batch brewing Scaling pour over"}, {"t": "Common Pour Over Mistakes", "u": "common-pour-over-mistakes.html", "d": "Brewing Technique", "i": "🌀", "c": "#B5612E", "s": "Most bad cups come from a short list of recurring errors — and nearly all have quick fixes once you can name them. This note is the field guide to the frequent stumbles. For a symptom first diagnostic walkthrough, pair it with the Pour Over", "k": "brewing-technique troubleshooting mistakes Common Pour Over Mistakes Pour over mistakes Brewing errors"}, {"t": "Recipes and Methods", "u": "recipes-and-methods.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "This is the home of every brewing recipe in the knowledge base — the part built to feed a future recipe app, so each note is precise, structured, and machine readable. A recipe is simply a documented set of choices about The Brew Ratio, Gri", "k": "recipes methods hub moc Recipes and Methods Recipe hub Pour over recipes"}, {"t": "How to Read a Coffee Recipe", "u": "how-to-read-a-coffee-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Every recipe in this knowledge base follows the same structure, deliberately, so that a human can scan it in five seconds and a machine can parse it without guessing. This note is the contract : it defines each field you'll see in the front", "k": "recipes schema reference How to Read a Coffee Recipe Recipe schema Recipe card schema"}, {"t": "Recipe Variables and Cup Outcomes", "u": "recipe-variables-and-cup-outcomes.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "A pour over has only a handful of knobs, and learning what each one does to the cup is the difference between following recipes and writing them. This note is a tuning guide: change one variable at a time, taste, and move deliberately. Almo", "k": "recipes tuning extraction Recipe Variables and Cup Outcomes Tuning a recipe Dialing in a recipe"}, {"t": "Official Brewer Recipes", "u": "official-brewer-recipes.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Official recipes are the methods published by the people who make the brewer — Hario for the V60, Kalita for the Wave, the Chemex Corporation, AeroPress, and so on. They matter because the device was designed around them : the geometry of t", "k": "recipes official index Official Brewer Recipes Manufacturer recipes Official recipes"}, {"t": "Hario V60 Official Recipe", "u": "hario-v60-official-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Hario's own method for the Hario V60 is the natural starting point for the world's most popular pour over cone. It is intentionally simple — a single bloom and two or three steady pours at a 1:15 The Brew Ratio — and it shows off exactly wh", "k": "recipes official v60 Hario V60 Official Recipe Hario V60 recipe V60 official method"}, {"t": "Kalita Wave Official Recipe", "u": "kalita-wave-official-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "The Kalita Wave is the friendly, forgiving cousin of the V60. Its flat bottom and three small drainage holes restrict and even out the flow, so the brewer's pour matters less and consistency comes easier — which is exactly what makes it a f", "k": "recipes official kalita Kalita Wave Official Recipe Kalita Wave recipe Kalita recipe"}, {"t": "⏳ Chemex Official Recipe", "u": "chemex-official-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "The Chemex is as much design object as brewer — a single piece of hourglass glass with a wooden collar, sold since 1941 and held in the Museum of Modern Art. Its defining feature is the proprietary bonded filter , up to 30% heavier than ord", "k": "recipes official chemex Chemex Official Recipe Chemex recipe Chemex method"}, {"t": "AeroPress Official Recipe", "u": "aeropress-official-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "The AeroPress was invented in 2005 by Aerobie's Alan Adler — the same engineer behind the record setting flying ring — to make a single, smooth, low bitterness cup fast. The original instructions are unlike any pour over: a short, relativel", "k": "recipes official aeropress immersion AeroPress Official Recipe AeroPress original recipe Classic AeroPress"}, {"t": "Clever Dripper Official Recipe", "u": "clever-dripper-official-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "The The Clever Dripper solves immersion's one inconvenience with a clever valve: a silicone stopper in the base that stays shut until you set the dripper on a cup , which opens it and drains the brew through a paper filter. So you get the f", "k": "recipes official clever immersion Clever Dripper Official Recipe Clever Dripper recipe Clever recipe"}, {"t": "OXO Rapid Brewer Recipe", "u": "oxo-rapid-brewer-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "The OXO Rapid Brewer is OXO's take on the The Clever Dripper idea: a flat bottom dripper with a shut off valve in the base so coffee steeps in full immersion, then drains through a flat paper filter when you press a lever or set it on the c", "k": "recipes official oxo immersion OXO Rapid Brewer Recipe OXO Rapid Brewer method OXO recipe"}, {"t": "Origami Dripper Recipe", "u": "origami-dripper-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "The Origami Dripper is the photogenic Japanese cone with twenty fluted ridges that gained fame after Tetsu Kasuya was seen using one. Its trick is versatility : the ridges hold the paper off the wall for fast, V60 like flow, and it accepts ", "k": "recipes official origami Origami Dripper Recipe Origami recipe Origami V60 recipe"}, {"t": "Competition Recipes", "u": "competition-recipes.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Competition recipes come from the The World Brewers Cup, the global stage where baristas brew filter coffee to a panel of judges and explain every choice. These routines are obsessively optimized — every gram, degree, and second justified o", "k": "recipes competition index Competition Recipes Brewers Cup recipes Championship recipes"}, {"t": "Tetsu Kasuya 4:6 Method", "u": "tetsu-kasuya-4-6-method.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "When Tetsu Kasuya won the 2016 World Brewers Cup, he introduced a framework so clear and adjustable that it became the default modern V60 method for serious home brewers worldwide. The 4:6 method divides the brew water into a first 40% that", "k": "recipes competition v60 kasuya Tetsu Kasuya 4:6 Method 4:6 method Kasuya 4-6"}, {"t": "Matt Winton Triangulation Method", "u": "matt-winton-triangulation-method.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Matt Winton won the 2021 World Brewers Cup with a deceptively plain looking V60 routine: five equal pours of 60 g each , every one with the same circular motion, spaced evenly in time. The name \"triangulation\" reflects his methodical, repea", "k": "recipes competition v60 winton Matt Winton Triangulation Method Matt Winton five pour Winton V60"}, {"t": "Stefanos Domatiotis Brewers Cup Recipe", "u": "stefanos-domatiotis-brewers-cup-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Stefanos Domatiotis of Taf Coffee in Athens won the 2014 World Brewers Cup, and his routine is remembered less for a single gimmick than for uncompromising precision and bean selection — an immaculate light roasted gesha brewed on a Hario V", "k": "recipes competition v60 domatiotis Stefanos Domatiotis Brewers Cup Recipe Stefanos Domatiotis recipe Domatiotis V60"}, {"t": "Emi Fukahori Brewers Cup Recipe", "u": "emi-fukahori-brewers-cup-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Emi Fukahori of MAME in Zurich won the 2018 World Brewers Cup — and did it with two memorable departures from the crowd. She brewed an experimental Laurina (a naturally low caffeine variety from Daterra in Brazil) rather than the near ubiqu", "k": "recipes competition v60 fukahori Emi Fukahori Brewers Cup Recipe Emi Fukahori recipe Fukahori V60"}, {"t": "Community Recipes", "u": "community-recipes.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Community recipes are the methods that spread through YouTube, blogs, forums, and roaster brew guides — refined by educators and professionals, then road tested by thousands of home brewers. They sit between the friendly Official Brewer Rec", "k": "recipes community index Community Recipes Creator recipes Roaster recipes"}, {"t": "James Hoffmann V60 Technique", "u": "james-hoffmann-v60-technique.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "James Hoffmann's \"Ultimate V60 Technique\" is probably the single most watched pour over tutorial in the world, and for good reason: it takes the Hario V60 and makes it consistent for normal people by replacing fiddly stirring with gentle sw", "k": "recipes community v60 hoffmann James Hoffmann V60 Technique Hoffmann V60 Ultimate V60 technique"}, {"t": "James Hoffmann Ultimate AeroPress", "u": "james-hoffmann-ultimate-aeropress.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "After testing the AeroPress's many myths on camera, James Hoffmann landed on a recipe that's almost provocatively simple — and it works. It throws out the inverted gymnastics and the cool water dogma in favor of an upright brew, a long gent", "k": "recipes community aeropress hoffmann immersion James Hoffmann Ultimate AeroPress Hoffmann AeroPress Ultimate AeroPress recipe"}, {"t": "The Rao Spin", "u": "the-rao-spin.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Scott Rao is one of coffee's most influential technical writers, and his V60 method is built around a single famous move: the spin . After the final pour, you give the dripper a firm rotational swirl to flatten the coffee bed and wash every", "k": "recipes community v60 rao The Rao Spin Rao spin Scott Rao V60"}, {"t": "Lance Hedrick Pour Over Technique", "u": "lance-hedrick-pour-over-technique.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Lance Hedrick — barista, former US AeroPress champion, and prolific educator — built a pour over approach for accessibility and repeatability on imperfect home gear . His signature moves are a coarser grind (to dodge the clogs and astringen", "k": "recipes community v60 hedrick Lance Hedrick Pour Over Technique Lance Hedrick V60 Hedrick pour over"}, {"t": "The Hario Switch Hybrid Method", "u": "the-hario-switch-hybrid-method.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "The Hario Switch is a V60 cone with a little spring loaded shut off valve in the base. Closed, it steeps coffee in full immersion like a The Clever Dripper; flicked open, it drains by percolation like an ordinary Hario V60. That one switch ", "k": "recipes community switch immersion hybrid The Hario Switch Hybrid Method Hario Switch recipe Switch hybrid brew"}, {"t": "Onyx Coffee Lab V60 Recipe", "u": "onyx-coffee-lab-v60-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Onyx Coffee Lab is one of the most decorated roasters in the United States, and its published V60 brew guide is a clean, professional template aimed at getting the best from its Light Roast and Specialty Coffee. The house style favors a blo", "k": "recipes community v60 onyx Onyx Coffee Lab V60 Recipe Onyx V60 recipe Onyx pour over"}, {"t": "The Standard V60 Recipe", "u": "the-standard-v60-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "This is the recipe to learn first — a clean, forgiving, beginner friendly default that strips pour over down to its essentials: one bloom, two simple pours, round numbers, and a 1:16 The Brew Ratio. There's nothing clever to get wrong, whic", "k": "recipes community v60 beginner The Standard V60 Recipe Standard V60 Beginner V60 recipe"}, {"t": "Iced and Cold Pour Over", "u": "iced-and-cold-pour-over.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Japanese style iced coffee — also called flash brewing — is pour over's best summer trick: you brew hot, directly onto ice , so the coffee is chilled the instant it's extracted. This is not cold brew. The hot water still extracts the bright", "k": "recipes community iced v60 Iced and Cold Pour Over Japanese iced coffee Flash brew"}, {"t": "Batch Pour Over Recipe", "u": "batch-pour-over-recipe.html", "d": "Recipes & Methods", "i": "📖", "c": "#C0492F", "s": "Brewing for a table is its own skill. Scaling a single cup recipe straight up doesn't quite work: a deep bed of coffee resists The Drawdown, holds more heat, and over extracts the bottom while the top runs fast. This recipe adapts the funda", "k": "recipes community batch chemex Batch Pour Over Recipe Batch brew recipe Large batch pour over"}, {"t": "Science and Extraction", "u": "science-and-extraction.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Every cup of pour over is a chemistry experiment you can drink. Hot water meets ground coffee, dissolves a fraction of its mass, and carries that fraction into your cup. This domain explains the science underneath the ritual — what actually", "k": "science extraction fundamentals hub Science and Extraction Coffee science Extraction science"}, {"t": "The Science of Extraction", "u": "the-science-of-extraction.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Extraction is the process of dissolving soluble compounds out of roasted, ground coffee and into water. A coffee bean is mostly insoluble plant matter — cellulose, fiber, structural carbohydrate — but roughly 28–30% of its mass can, in prin", "k": "science extraction fundamentals The Science of Extraction Extraction How extraction works"}, {"t": "Solubility and What Dissolves", "u": "solubility-and-what-dissolves.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Not everything in coffee dissolves at the same speed. Brewing extracts compounds in a rough sequence , and that sequence is the secret behind why timing, grind, and temperature matter so much. The early arrivals taste bright and acidic; the", "k": "science extraction chemistry Solubility and What Dissolves Solubility What dissolves in coffee"}, {"t": "Extraction Yield and Strength", "u": "extraction-yield-and-strength.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Two numbers describe almost everything about a brew, and the key insight is that they are independent . Extraction yield (EY%) is how much of the coffee dissolved. Strength (TDS) is how concentrated the resulting liquid is. You can have a s", "k": "science extraction measurement Extraction Yield and Strength Extraction yield EY and TDS"}, {"t": "Total Dissolved Solids (TDS)", "u": "total-dissolved-solids-tds.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Total Dissolved Solids (TDS) is the share of a brewed coffee's mass that is dissolved coffee rather than water. If a cup is 1.35% TDS , then 1.35% of the liquid's weight is dissolved solids and the remaining 98.65% is water. TDS is the scie", "k": "science extraction measurement Total Dissolved Solids (TDS) Brew TDS Strength"}, {"t": "The Coffee Brewing Control Chart", "u": "the-coffee-brewing-control-chart.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "The Coffee Brewing Control Chart is the classic map of brewing space: a graph with Total Dissolved Solids (TDS) on the vertical axis and Extraction Yield and Strength on the horizontal axis. Any brew you make plots as a single dot somewhere", "k": "science extraction measurement history The Coffee Brewing Control Chart Brewing Control Chart Coffee Compass"}, {"t": "Refractometers and Measuring Extraction", "u": "refractometers-and-measuring-extraction.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "A refractometer is the instrument that turns brewing from intuition into measurement. It reads the Total Dissolved Solids (TDS) of your cup, and from TDS plus a little arithmetic you can calculate the Extraction Yield and Strength — the two", "k": "science extraction measurement tools Refractometers and Measuring Extraction Refractometer Measuring extraction"}, {"t": "Under-Extraction and Over-Extraction", "u": "under-extraction-and-over-extraction.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "If a brew tastes off, the first question is almost always: did I take too little or too much from the coffee? Under extraction stops too early on the Solubility and What Dissolves, leaving the cup dominated by the first, sour leaning compou", "k": "science extraction troubleshooting Under-Extraction and Over-Extraction Under-extraction Over-extraction"}, {"t": "Channeling and Uneven Extraction", "u": "channeling-and-uneven-extraction.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "The The Coffee Brewing Control Chart reports a single average extraction yield — but a brew is millions of particles, and water does not treat them equally. Channeling is when water carves preferential paths through the coffee bed, racing t", "k": "science extraction troubleshooting Channeling and Uneven Extraction Channeling Uneven extraction"}, {"t": "The Role of Temperature in Extraction", "u": "the-role-of-temperature-in-extraction.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Heat is energy, and extraction is an energy driven process — so water temperature is one of the most powerful levers on how fast and how completely coffee dissolves. Hotter water dissolves more solids, faster; cooler water extracts gently a", "k": "science extraction water The Role of Temperature in Extraction Temperature and extraction Brew temperature science"}, {"t": "Grind Size and Surface Area", "u": "grind-size-and-surface-area.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Grind size is the master lever of extraction, and the reason is pure geometry: smaller particles expose vastly more surface area to the water, and surface area is where dissolution happens. Halve a particle's diameter and you roughly double", "k": "science extraction grinding Grind Size and Surface Area Surface area Particle size and extraction"}, {"t": "CO2, Degassing, and the Bloom Science", "u": "co2-degassing-and-the-bloom-science.html", "d": "Science & Extraction", "i": "🔬", "c": "#5E6C99", "s": "Pour fresh coffee its first splash of water and the bed swells, foams, and exhales — the famous bloom . That eruption is carbon dioxide escaping. Roasting fills coffee with CO2, the gas slowly leaks out over days ( degassing ), and how much", "k": "science extraction freshness chemistry \"CO2 Degassing and the Bloom Science\" Degassing Bloom science"}, {"t": "Tasting and Sensory", "u": "tasting-and-sensory.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "Everything else in this knowledge base — the The Coffee Plant — Arabica and Robusta, the Coffee Processing Methods, the Grind Size for Pour Over, the Water for Coffee, the The Brew Ratio, the The Science of Extraction — exists to serve one ", "k": "tasting sensory moc hub Tasting and Sensory Sensory evaluation Tasting coffee"}, {"t": "How to Taste Coffee", "u": "how-to-taste-coffee.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "Tasting coffee well is a deliberate act, not a sip. The goal is to gather as much sensory information as possible from each mouthful and to do it the same way every time, so that differences you notice come from the coffee rather than from ", "k": "tasting sensory technique How to Taste Coffee Tasting technique How to taste"}, {"t": "Cupping", "u": "cupping.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "Cupping is the coffee industry's standardized method for tasting and scoring coffee. Roasters, buyers, graders, and competitors all use it because it strips away nearly every brewing variable — no The Dripper Explained, no Pouring Technique", "k": "tasting sensory cupping protocol Cupping Coffee cupping The cupping protocol"}, {"t": "The Coffee Flavor Wheel", "u": "the-coffee-flavor-wheel.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "The Coffee Taster's Flavor Wheel is a circular diagram that organizes the flavors found in coffee from broad, general categories at its center to precise, specific descriptors at its rim. First published by the Specialty Coffee Association ", "k": "tasting sensory vocabulary reference The Coffee Flavor Wheel Flavor wheel Coffee taster's flavor wheel"}, {"t": "Acidity in Coffee", "u": "acidity-in-coffee.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "In coffee tasting, acidity is a virtue, not a fault. It is the bright, lively, mouth watering quality that makes a great light roast Kenyan taste like blackcurrant or a Colombian taste like green apple. Newcomers often hear \"acidic\" as a wa", "k": "tasting sensory acidity chemistry Acidity in Coffee Coffee acidity Brightness"}, {"t": "Sweetness and Body", "u": "sweetness-and-body.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "If Acidity in Coffee is coffee's brightness, sweetness is its reward and body is its weight. Together they form the backbone of a satisfying cup: sweetness makes flavors pleasant and balanced, while body gives the coffee presence and textur", "k": "tasting sensory sweetness body mouthfeel Sweetness and Body Coffee body Mouthfeel"}, {"t": "Aroma and Flavor Compounds", "u": "aroma-and-flavor-compounds.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "When you describe a coffee as smelling of jasmine, blueberry, or roasted hazelnut, you are reading the work of volatile aromatic compounds — molecules light enough to evaporate into the air and reach the smell receptors in your nose. Coffee", "k": "tasting sensory aroma chemistry Aroma and Flavor Compounds Coffee aroma Volatile compounds"}, {"t": "Identifying Defects and Off-Flavors", "u": "identifying-defects-and-off-flavors.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "Learning what good coffee tastes like is only half of palate training; the other half is recognizing what is wrong and tracing it to a cause. Off flavors come from two very different places: defects baked into the coffee before you ever tou", "k": "tasting sensory defects troubleshooting Identifying Defects and Off-Flavors Coffee defects Off-flavors"}, {"t": "Building Your Palate", "u": "building-your-palate.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "A trained palate is not a gift you are born with — it is a skill you build through deliberate practice, exactly like learning an instrument or a language. The good news is that the underlying hardware is roughly equal across healthy people;", "k": "tasting sensory training practice Building Your Palate Palate training Training your palate"}, {"t": "Describing Coffee — The Vocabulary", "u": "describing-coffee-the-vocabulary.html", "d": "Tasting & Sensory", "i": "👅", "c": "#B14A7A", "s": "Once you can perceive what is in a cup, the final skill is describing it — putting words to flavor precisely enough that another person can picture the coffee they have never tasted. This is harder than it sounds, because flavor language is", "k": "tasting sensory vocabulary language Describing Coffee — The Vocabulary Coffee vocabulary Tasting language"}, {"t": "Culture and Industry", "u": "culture-and-industry.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "Pour over is more than a brewing technique — it is a culture , an industry , and a community that together turned a niche manual method into a global craft. This is the map of the human side of coffee: the people who grow, roast, sell, brew", "k": "culture industry hub moc Culture and Industry Coffee culture Pour over industry"}, {"t": "The Specialty Coffee Industry", "u": "the-specialty-coffee-industry.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "The specialty coffee industry is the slice of the global coffee trade built around quality rather than commodity volume — coffees evaluated, scored, and sold on the basis of how good they taste, not merely how cheaply they can be produced. ", "k": "culture industry specialty sca The Specialty Coffee Industry Specialty coffee industry Specialty coffee market"}, {"t": "Notable Roasters", "u": "notable-roasters.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "A handful of specialty roasters did more than sell beans — they defined the aesthetic of modern filter coffee: lighter roasts, transparent sourcing, named producers, and recipes published for the world to copy. This note profiles a few of t", "k": "culture industry roasters brands Notable Roasters Specialty roasters Influential coffee roasters"}, {"t": "Coffee Shops and Cafe Culture", "u": "coffee-shops-and-cafe-culture.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "The café is where pour over became public ritual. Long before most people owned a Hario V60 at home, they encountered manual brewing across a counter — watching a barista weigh beans, bloom the grounds, and pour in slow concentric circles. ", "k": "culture industry cafe third-wave Coffee Shops and Cafe Culture Cafe culture Third-wave cafes"}, {"t": "The World Brewers Cup", "u": "the-world-brewers-cup.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "The World Brewers Cup (WBrC) is the competition that put manual filter brewing on a global stage. Organized under the Specialty Coffee Association as one of the World Coffee Championships, it asks a deceptively simple question: who can brew", "k": "culture industry competition brewers-cup The World Brewers Cup World Brewers Cup Brewers Cup"}, {"t": "Coffee Gear Brands", "u": "coffee-gear-brands.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "Pour over culture runs on gear , and a surprisingly small set of brands defines the modern brewer's bench. Some are decades old manufacturers from Japan and Germany; others are startups born from the The Modern Pour Over Renaissance. Togeth", "k": "culture industry gear brands Coffee Gear Brands Pour over brands Coffee equipment brands"}, {"t": "Baristas and Home Brewers", "u": "baristas-and-home-brewers.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "Pour over culture is carried by two overlapping groups of people: the professional barista behind the café bar, and the home brewer chasing the same cup on a kitchen counter. The remarkable thing about specialty coffee is how porous that li", "k": "culture industry barista community Baristas and Home Brewers Baristas Home brewing community"}, {"t": "Direct Trade and Coffee Sourcing", "u": "direct-trade-and-coffee-sourcing.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "How a roaster buys green coffee is one of the most contested topics in the industry — partly because the stakes are real (farmer livelihoods) and partly because the language is loose. \"Direct trade,\" \"Fair Trade,\" \"relationship coffee,\" and", "k": "culture industry sourcing ethics Direct Trade and Coffee Sourcing Direct trade Coffee sourcing"}, {"t": "Sustainability in Coffee", "u": "sustainability-in-coffee.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "Coffee has a sustainability problem on every axis at once: the plant is threatened by a warming climate, the farmers who grow it are squeezed by economics, and brewing it generates real waste and emissions. For a culture that prizes the cra", "k": "culture industry sustainability climate Sustainability in Coffee Coffee sustainability Coffee and climate"}, {"t": "Coffee Online — Communities and Content", "u": "coffee-online-communities-and-content.html", "d": "Culture & Industry", "i": "🏭", "c": "#8567A8", "s": "If the café introduced people to pour over, the internet taught them to do it at home . The modern coffee renaissance is, to an unusual degree, a media phenomenon: YouTube videos, forums, blogs, and social feeds carried café grade technique", "k": "culture industry online content youtube Coffee Online — Communities and Content Coffee online Coffee YouTube and forums"}, {"t": "Reference", "u": "reference.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "The Reference domain is the quick lookup toolkit of this knowledge base — the shelf you reach for mid brew when you need an answer fast rather than a deep read. Where the other eleven domains teach concepts, these notes condense them into g", "k": "reference hub moc Reference Reference hub Reference toolkit"}, {"t": "Glossary of Coffee Terms", "u": "glossary-of-coffee-terms.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "A working brewer's A to Z. Each entry is a short, plain language definition; where a term has its own full note, the term links to it. For pronunciation and flavor vocabulary used at the cupping table, pair this with Describing Coffee — The", "k": "reference glossary terminology Glossary of Coffee Terms Coffee glossary Coffee terms"}, {"t": "Pour Over Troubleshooting Guide", "u": "pour-over-troubleshooting-guide.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "Something tastes off. Before you blame the beans, work through the symptom tables below — most bad cups trace back to one or two variables. The golden rule: change one thing at a time so you learn what each adjustment does. For the theory b", "k": "reference troubleshooting brewing Pour Over Troubleshooting Guide Troubleshooting Fixing your cup"}, {"t": "Master Index", "u": "master-index.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "The complete map of the knowledge base — every note, grouped by its domain and listed in reading order. Use this as the table of contents for the whole vault: skim a domain heading, then jump straight to the note you need. Each domain also ", "k": "reference index moc Master Index Index Vault map"}, {"t": "Brew Method Comparison Table", "u": "brew-method-comparison-table.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "Nine common brewers, side by side. Pour over (percolation) and immersion methods extract differently and reward different goals — clarity versus body, control versus convenience. Use this table to pick a brewer or to understand why two devi", "k": "reference equipment comparison Brew Method Comparison Table Brewer comparison Dripper comparison"}, {"t": "Coffee Measurement and Conversion Tables", "u": "coffee-measurement-and-conversion-tables.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "The numbers you need at the scale, in one place. Brew by weight , not volume — a tablespoon of coffee varies wildly with bean density and grind, but grams never lie. These tables turn ratios, doses, and temperatures into the exact figures y", "k": "reference measurement conversion Coffee Measurement and Conversion Tables Conversion tables Coffee math"}, {"t": "Recommended Reading and Resources", "u": "recommended-reading-and-resources.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "Where to go when this vault leaves you wanting more. The coffee world is rich with excellent books, channels, and communities; below are the ones most worth a brewer's time, lightly annotated. None of this replaces brewing daily — but good ", "k": "reference resources learning Recommended Reading and Resources Resources Further reading"}, {"t": "Frequently Asked Questions", "u": "frequently-asked-questions.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "The questions almost every new pour over brewer asks, answered concisely — with a link to go deeper. If your question is \"why does my coffee taste sour/bitter/weak,\" skip straight to the Pour Over Troubleshooting Guide. Otherwise, start her", "k": "reference faq beginner Frequently Asked Questions FAQ Common questions"}, {"t": "Pour Over Quick Start Checklist", "u": "pour-over-quick-start-checklist.html", "d": "Reference", "i": "📚", "c": "#6F8A86", "s": "Everything you need to brew a genuinely good first cup, in order, with nothing skipped. Print it, tape it to your kettle, and follow it top to bottom. The recipe baked into this checklist is The Standard V60 Recipe — once it feels routine, ", "k": "reference beginner checklist Pour Over Quick Start Checklist Quick start Beginner checklist"}];